<section class="sec reveal" id="qb-cleanup-undeposited-funds-definition" style="padding-top:24px;">
  <div class="ct read read--doc">
    <div class="eyebrow" style="margin-bottom:8px;">In plain terms</div>
    <h2 class="h2" style="margin-bottom:18px;">What Undeposited Funds is &mdash; and how it piles up.</h2>
    <div class="prose">
      <p>Undeposited Funds is a default account QuickBooks creates to hold payments you&rsquo;ve received but not yet deposited. The logic is sound: when you take several customer payments to the bank at once, they hit your statement as a single combined deposit. Undeposited Funds lets you record each payment as it comes in, then group them into one deposit that matches that real-world deposit slip &mdash; so the books line up with the bank.</p>
      <p>The pileup happens when payments go <em>in</em> but never get grouped into a deposit. Record a payment and skip the matching deposit, and the money sits in Undeposited Funds forever. Let the bank feed add a deposit <em>separately</em> from the invoice payment, and the same income is counted twice. Do either repeatedly &mdash; or inherit a file where a prior bookkeeper already did &mdash; and the balance grows into a list of stuck payments that no longer resemble anything that hit the bank. The result is overstated or duplicated income and a bank account that won&rsquo;t reconcile. The fix is methodical, not a delete: identify the stuck payments, group the real ones into deposits that match the bank, remove genuine duplicates carefully, and reconcile.</p>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

